04483nam a22005055i 9780773563001DE-B159720240306124542.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t19911991xxc    fo  d z      eng d  a97807735630017 a10.1515/97807735630012doi  a(DE-B1597)654480  a(OCoLC)1192329608  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxccCA 4aPR9199.3.M617bZ765 1991eb 7aLIT0040802bisacsh04a813/.541 aO'Donoghue, Jo, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aBrian Moore :bA Critical Study /cJo O'Donoghue. 1aMontreal ;aKingston ;aLondon ;aChicago : bMcGill-Queen's University Press, c[1991] 4c©1991  a1 online resource (288 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFront Matter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- tThe Early Belfast Novels -- tBeleaguered Catholicism -- tReligion without Belief— -- tThe Making of an Ulster Catholic— -- tVictims of Religion -- tNovels of Exile and Escape -- tThe Search for the Self -- tThe Giving of Voice — -- tThe Fixed Centre — -- tThe Multiple Perception— -- tConclusion -- tBelief in A Secular World -- tThe Quest for a Higher Belief -- tCreating a God— -- tThe Temptation of the Unbeliever— -- tThe Cruelty of Belief— -- tConclusion -- tPolitics as Morality -- tA New Engagement with the Actual -- tFaith Versus Materialism— -- tThe Killers' Choice — -- tNotes -- tSelect Bibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aMoore grew up in Northern Ireland and as a young man spent a number of years travelling throughout Europe while working for the British Ministry of War Transport. In 1948 he left for Montreal, where he began his literary career. While living in Canada he supported his writing by working as a proof-reader, reporter, and pseudonymous thriller-writer. He wrote his first serious novel, Judith Hearne, during a stay of several months in a log cabin in Quebec's Laurentian Mountains. After eleven years in Canada, he was awarded a Guggenheim fellowship and moved to New York. He eventually moved to Hollywood to write a film for Alfred Hitchcock and now lives in Malibu, California. Jo O'Donoghue identifies Moore as a writer particularly interested both in questions of religion and in a world he believes to have largely abandoned traditional spiritual values. Moore's Irish Catholic upbringing, she demonstrates, has located him in an enclosed, self-sufficient community with a strong sense of the spiritual. O'Donoghue regards Moore as remarkable among modern male novelists for the depth of his interest in women and the sensitivity and acuteness of his insights into women's psychology. Although Moore, in a literary career spanning more than thirty years, has published sixteen novels and one work of reportage and has won numerous literary prizes, he has only recently attracted the sort of consistent critical acclaim which is his due. The Colour of Blood finally secured recognition for him as one of the truly important novelists of the late twentieth century. O'Donoghue's study is the first major critical analysis of the work of this gifted and accomplished writer.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Canadian.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package Pre-2010z978311127416408iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Upgrade eBook-Package pre 2010z978311127724040uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978077356300140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780773563001423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780773563001/original  a978-3-11-127416-4  ACUP Complete eBook-Package Pre-2010b2010  a978-3-11-127724-0  ACUP Upgrade eBook-Package pre 2010b2010  aGBV-deGruyter-alles